'''Up and Vanished''' is an investigative journalism [[podcast]] hosted by [[Payne Lindsey]]. The series takes an in-depth look into the cases of people who have gone missing. The show is produced by Tenderfoot TV.

==Series overview==
The series explores cases of people who went missing or have disappeared in order to discover what happened to them and their whereabouts. The first season dealt with the disappearance of [[Tara Grinstead]],<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.wrbl.com/news/atlanta-filmmaker-reignites-interest-in-tara-grinstead-disappearance_20171130080115743/870024144 |title= Atlanta filmmaker reignites interest in Tara Grinstead disappearance |work= WRBL News  |date=2016-12-28 |accessdate=2018-03-02}}</ref> a beauty queen and school teacher who disappeared in [[Ocilla, Georgia]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.myajc.com/news/crime--law/ajc-watchdog-grinstead-murder-mystery-hampered-georgia-secrecy/7dt4ntQ7uqOhGuBMmSSRBJ/ |title= AJC Watchdog: Grinstead murder mystery hampered by Georgia secrecy |work= The Atlanta Journal Constitution |date=2017-03-16 |accessdate=2018-03-02}}</ref> Season 2 aired in August 2018 focusing on the [[Disappearance of Kristal Reisinger|disappearance of Kristal Reisinger]] in [[Crestone, Colorado]].

==History==
In 2016, documentary filmmaker [[Payne Lindsey]] of Tenderfoot TV studios began researching the Tara Grinstead cold case as a possibility for a new film.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Mallenbaum|first1=Carly|title=Podcast Pick: 'Up and Vanished' cracks open 12-year-old cold case|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/entertainthis/2017/03/26/up-and-vanished-podcast/99671984/|accessdate=22 February 2018|agency=USA Today|date=March 26, 2017}}</ref> Lindsey became aware of Tara Grinstead's case because of its reputation as the largest case file in Georgia state history, but he also soon discovered that his grandmother's friend was one of the last people to see Tara alive.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Locker|first1=Melissa|title=How 'Up and Vanished' Podcast Helped Solve Cold Murder Case| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/how-up-and-vanished-podcast-helped-solve-cold-murder-case-w472620|accessdate=22 February 2018|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 17, 2017}}</ref> Inspired by the popular NPR podcast [[Serial (podcast)|Serial]], Lindsey recorded his research in a podcast style format detailing the specifics of the case, as well as interviews with key witnesses. The podcast, ''Up and Vanished,'' premiered on Apple Podcasts and the show's website, [https://upandvanished.com/ upandvanished.com], on August 7, 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://upandvanished.com/|title=Up and Vanished|publisher=Tenderfood TV|accessdate=22 February 2018}}</ref> Soon after the podcast's release it made the top charts and began receiving attention and notoriety within the small Ocilla, Georgia community.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Beimfohr|first1=Chelsea|title=Georgia Supreme Court hears gag order arguments in Grinstead case| url=http://www.13wmaz.com/news/local/tara-grinstead-case/georgia-supreme-court-to-hear-gag-order-arguments-in-grinstead-case/485434231|accessdate=22 February 2018|agency=WMAZ|date=October 24, 2017}}</ref> The podcast is credited with reigniting the discussion on the case after it sat dormant for twelve years. In the statement by the [[Georgia Bureau of Investigation]] announcing the arrest of Ryan Alexander Duke in connection to the murder, the GBI's spokesperson thanked the media for keeping the public interested in the case.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Locker|first1=Melissa|title=How 'Up and Vanished' Podcast Helped Solve Cold Murder Case| url=https://www.rollingstone.com/culture/how-up-and-vanished-podcast-helped-solve-cold-murder-case-w472620|accessdate=23 May 2018|work=Rolling Stone|date=March 17, 2017}}</ref>

